Task 1: Choose your favorite dataset

The datateachr package by Hayley Boyce and Jordan Bourak currently composed of 7 semi-tidy datasets for educational purposes. Here is a brief description of each dataset:

  • apt_buildings: Acquired courtesy of The City of Torontos Open Data Portal. It currently has 3455 rows and 37 columns.

  • building_permits: Acquired courtesy of The City of Vancouvers Open Data Portal. It currently has 20680 rows and 14 columns.

  • cancer_sample: Acquired courtesy of UCI Machine Learning Repository. It currently has 569 rows and 32 columns.

  • flow_sample: Acquired courtesy of The Government of Canadas Historical Hydrometric Database. It currently has 218 rows and 7 columns.

  • parking_meters: Acquired courtesy of The City of Vancouvers Open Data Portal. It currently has 10032 rows and 22 columns.

  • steam_games: Acquired courtesy of Kaggle. It currently has 40833 rows and 21 columns.

  • vancouver_trees: Acquired courtesy of The City of Vancouvers Open Data Portal. It currently has 146611 rows and 20 columns.

Exercise A: Make a new tibble with a subset of your data, with variables and observations that you are interested in exploring. (No.8) Here I choose to explore the number of elevators at each apartment building: How are the number of elevators distributed among buildings? I believe the outcome can benefit future research on architecture design, facilities for people with mobility difficulties, resource distribution, etc.

Visualization rationale: at first I thought to use geom_col(), but building_count ranges from 1337 to 1 make the visualization difficult. So I choose geom_count(), using position channel (horizontal and vertical) together with size channel (the size of the circle links to building_count) to present the data.

#set up
library (ggplot2)
#create a new tibble named elevator 
elevator <-apt_buildings %>%
  select(no_of_elevators) %>%
  filter(!is.na(no_of_elevators))%>% #cleaned the data by filtering out the null data
  count(no_of_elevators)%>%
  rename(building_count=n)
#visualize the distribution 
elevator_plot <-ggplot(elevator, aes(no_of_elevators, building_count)) +
  geom_count(aes(size=building_count))+
  labs(title="The Distribution of Elevator", x= "The Number of Elevators", y= "The Number of Buildings")+
  theme_minimal()
print(elevator_plot)

Exercise B: Investigate how many missing values there are per variable. Can you find a way to plot this? (No.3)

I choose this task because it can help deepen my understanding of the dataset.For example, if one variable has too many missing value, this variable may not be qualified to conduct future research. This can also help users to explore the initial data collection process: which variable misses more values and requires more attention when we collect it next time.

Visualization rationale: There are many variable_names, so I put it on the y axis instead of x.

missing_counts <- apt_buildings %>%
    summarize_all(~sum(is.na(.)))%>% #count missing values per variable 
    gather(key=variable_names, value=missing_count) %>% #make it from wide to long format to prepare for ggplot
    ggplot(aes(x=missing_count,y=reorder(variable_names,missing_count))) +
    geom_col()+
    labs(title="The Number of Missing Values in Each Variable", x= "The Number of Missing Values", y= "Variable Names")
print(missing_counts)

Exercise C:Explore the relationship between 2 variables in a plot.

I choose this task because it fits the research question I listed previously: What is the relationship (or is there a relationship) between pets_allowed and property_type? As both pets_allowed and property_type are categorical variables, I choose to use contingency table and chi-square test to analyze. This plot can benefit further discussion in social science with topics like whats individuals rights in public space, the boundary of public and private, etc.

Visualization rationale: Because its a contingency table, I choose a mosaic plot to visualize it. Because the count is different among the three categories of property type, I use percentage. Green for yes and red for no, fits color symbolism.

#clean the missing value in pets_allowed indicated by Exercise B
filter_missing_pets<-apt_buildings%>%
  filter(!is.na(pets_allowed))
#create a contingency table and conduct chi-square test
contingency_table <- table(filter_missing_pets$pets_allowed, filter_missing_pets$property_type)
chi_square <- chisq.test(contingency_table)

print(contingency_table)
##      
##       PRIVATE SOCIAL HOUSING TCHC
##   NO      523             28   50
##   YES    2281            207  276
print(chi_square)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  contingency_table
## X-squared = 8.2744, df = 2, p-value = 0.01597
# Create a new data frame from the contingency table for visualization
contingency_df <- as.data.frame(contingency_table)%>%
  `colnames<-`(c("PetsAllowed", "PropertyType", "Count")) %>%
    group_by(PropertyType) %>%
    mutate(Percentage = (Count / sum(Count)) * 100)
# Create a mosaic plot 
mosaic_plot <- 
  ggplot(contingency_df, aes(x = factor(PropertyType), y = Percentage, fill = PetsAllowed)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(title = "Mosaic Plot of Property Type and Pets Allowed",
    x = "Property Type",
    y = "Percentage",
    fill = "Pets Allowed"
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", "green")) +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(Percentage), "%")), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size = 3) +
  theme_minimal()
print(mosaic_plot)

Exercise D: Use a density plot to explore any of your variables (No.8)

In this exercise, I choose to use density plot to present the density of buildings built year. This plot is valuable because it can help audience to understand the history of apartment building construction in Toronto.

Visualization rationale: A common use of a density plot is to visualize the distribution of data over a time period.

density_plot <- apt_buildings%>%
  filter(!is.na(year_built))%>% #filter out the missing value indicated by Exercise B
  ggplot(aes(year_built)) +
  geom_density() +  
  labs(
    title = "Density Plot",
    x = "Year Built",
    y = "Density"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

print(density_plot)

The document should read sensibly from top to bottom, with no major continuity errors. An example of a major continuity error is having a data set listed for Task 3 that is not part of one of the data sets listed in Task 1.

Error-free code (3 points)

For full marks, all code in the document should run without error. 1 point deduction if most code runs without error, and 2 points deduction if more than 50% of the code throws an error.

Main README (1 point)

There should be a file named README.md at the top level of your repository. Its contents should automatically appear when you visit the repository on GitHub.

Minimum contents of the README file:

  • In a sentence or two, explains what this repository is, so that future-you or someone else stumbling on your repository can be oriented to the repository.
  • In a sentence or two (or more??), briefly explains how to engage with the repository. You can assume the person reading knows the material from STAT 545A. Basically, if a visitor to your repository wants to explore your project, what should they know?

Once you get in the habit of making README files, and seeing more README files in other projects, youll wonder how you ever got by without them! They are tremendously helpful.

Output (1 point)

All output is readable, recent and relevant:

  • All Rmd files have been knitted to their output md files.
  • All knitted md files are viewable without errors on Github. Examples of errors: Missing plots, Sorry about that, but we cant show files that are this big right now messages, error messages from broken R code
  • All of these output files are up-to-date that is, they havent fallen behind after the source (Rmd) files have been updated.
  • There should be no relic output files. For example, if you were knitting an Rmd to html, but then changed the output to be only a markdown file, then the html file is a relic and should be deleted.

(0.5 point deduction if any of the above criteria are not met. 1 point deduction if most or all of the above criteria are not met.)

Our recommendation: right before submission, delete all output files, and re-knit each milestones Rmd file, so that everything is up to date and relevant. Then, after your final commit and push to Github, CHECK on Github to make sure that everything looks the way you intended!

Tagged release (0.5 points)

Youve tagged a release for Milestone 1.
